sentiment
in favor of the Italian among those who had
been chiefly accustomed to see Peterchen enact
the busy, important, dignified, local functionary.
Attention was now paid to the first wants of the
travellers, who had great need of refreshments
after
the fatigues and exposure of the day. To
obtain
the latter, Roger de Blonay insisted that they
should ascend to his castle, in whose grate the
welcoming
beacon still blazed. By means of
chars
-banc
, the peculiar vehicle of the country, the
